{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_dioptase_ver02/data/sn90050367/00516990387/1927031701/0097.xml":{"full_text":"FORFEITED LAND\n|t BEINGREDEEMED\nMach Land Taken for Talas to Bo\nia Cultivation Again.\n(Prom Sunday\u2019s Arkansas Gazette)\nIn an interview with a member of\ntile State Highway Department a rep\nSresentative from the Little Rock\nieal Estate Board learned that the\nprospects seem very good for the\ncultivation of a much larger acreage\nof farm lands through the state high\nway than last year.\nBecause of the highway taxes\nsomething like 500,000 acres of farm\nlands throughout the state have been\nNEW SPRING\nK, FOOTWEAR\nNow Being Received\nFor Ladies and Misses we\nrecommend\nCONSTANT COMFORT\n1. Cushion insole that con\nforms with the natural\noutline of the foot.\n2. Flexible sole insuring\nglovelike freedom for\nwoman\u2019s active hours.\nHeavier sole for more\ncomfortable walking.\n3. A toe and heel that give\nplenty of room and\ngraceful style.\n4. Rubber heel to cushion\nevery step.\n5. Reinforced moulded\ncounter to prevent Tun\ning over at heel.\n6. Rigid steel shank giv\ning needed support to\nthe sensitive foot arch.\n7. Tite-fit ankle, holding\nthe heel sfhugly and the\nstocking smoothly; pre\nventing slipping and\ngapping.\nAll of which positively\ninsure new-fashioned, youth\nful style with good wear\nand perfect ease\u2014at a mod\nerate price\u2014$3 to 7.\nFor Sale by\nSAM W. BURD\nFront Street.\nNORFLEET NORFLEET\nAttorneys-at-Law\nHoney to Loan on Real\nEstate.'\nOffice over Williams\u2019\nBarber Shop\nPractice in all Courts\u2014\nFederal and State\nR. J. WILLIAMS\nATTORNEY-AT-LAW\nFORREST CITY. ARK.\nS. S. HARGRAVES\nLawyer\n914 Exchange Bldg.\nMEMPHIS, TENN.\nC W. NORTON\nj. Attorney-* t -La w\nOffice in Roll wage Bldg.\nFORREST CITY, ARK.\nK; MANN* MANN\n\nAttorney* rt-Uw\nOffice in Mann Building _\nPractice in ell the Courts\nFORREST CITY, ARK.\nr v.\nW. S. ALLEY V\nFORREST CITY, ARK.\nLifa Insurance. Farm Loans\nOffice orar\nBank of Eastern Arkansas^\nforfeited for taxes. A large portion!\nof this land was forfeited during the\npast four or five years.\nThe passage of the Martineau road\nbill, which will distribute the tax\nfor the highways over the entire\nstate instead of confining it to a\nfew, will bring much relief to the\nfarmers, according to the Highway\nDepartment, and will release these\nabandoned farms for cultivation.\n17,000 Acres Redeemed.\nSince the first of the year about\n17,000 acres of forfeited farm lands\nhave been redeemed. More applica\ntions for redemptions are coming in\nevery day. The fact that the bill\nhas been passed and a knowledge of\njust what it will mean to these far\nmers who have had to give up their\nlands because they could not pay the\ntaxes has not yet been realized by\nall those whose lands went back to\nthe state. But notices are going out\nto them every day and the Highway\nDepartment thinks that just as soon\nas the real import of the bill and\nits effect on the farmers is actually\nrealized, many more farms will be\nredeemed and put under cultivation.\nSomething like $25,000 or $30,000\nhas come into the state school fund\nfrom these redemptions.\nOther Land Is Donated.\nIn addition to the farms that are\nbeing put back under cultivation\nthrough redemption are numerous\nother farms which have been secured\nthrough state donations and are be\ning cultivated.\nUnder the laws of the state for\nfeited lands may be disposed of by\nthe state through donation, a plan\ncorresponding to the government's\nplan of disposing of lands through\nhomesteading.\nA tract not exceeding 160 acres\nmay be donated under certain condi\ntions. A continuous residence of\nthree years is required before a do\nnation deed is given. Also, a house\ntenable at all seasons of the year\nmust be built, and at least five acres\nof the land must be cleared and\nplaced under cultivation.\nA good many of the farms which\nwere forfeited for taxes have al\nready been transferred to other far\nmers through the donation plan and\nare now under cultivation.\nWith the new road law in opera\ntion it is believed that a great many\nmore of the forfeited lands will be\nredeemed, placing Arkansas in a\nmuch better economic condition than\nnumbers of other states where farms\nare now being forfeited in large num\nbers through inability of the owners\nto pay the taxes.\nSTEERING EASE OF\nVITAL IMPORTANCE\n\u201cAn important point truck owners\noften overlook in making their pur\nchases is the ease with which the\ntruck can be handled,\" said Leo\nGrobmyer, of the Grobmyer Garage,\nlocal Dodge Brothers dealer.\n\u201cIt is important because it makes\nall the difference in the world in the\nprevention of accidents. A truck\nresponds to every touch of the wheel\nand braking mechanism is less likely\nto figure in accidents than one which\nis lacking in those qualities. Power\nful, easy braking is probably one of\nthe largest factors in truck driving\nwho really know their advantages.\nAfiyAne can observe the ease with\nwhich one of these trucks or com\nmercial cars travels through the\nheaviest traffic. It stops and starts\nand is handled with the ease of a pas\nsenger car.\u201d\n*500,000 OR RELIGION\nCardiff.\u2014P. B. Downing inherited\n$500,000 from hie grandfather\u2019s\nestate, but he will forfeit this if he\nchanges his religion.\nNUDE MANIAC ESCAPES\nLiverpool.\u2014Henry C. Morton, in\nmate of the city asylum, escaped\nwithout any clothing on, but was re\ncaptured in a street chase.\nCONVICTED BY SILK\nParis.\u2014Mile. Jeanne Larricuex\nwas sent to prison for fraud because,\nwhen arrested for begging, she had\nsilk underwear beneath a ragged\ndress.\nCOMMISSIONER\u2019S SALE\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN,\nThat in pursuance of the authority\nand directions contained in the de\ncretal order of the Chancery Court\nof St. Francis County, made and en\ntered on the 28th day of February.\nA. D., 1927, in a-certain cause (No.\n4844) then pending therein between\nThe Union Central Life Insurance\nCo., and Louis Breiling, Trustee,\ncomplainants, and Amanda Johnson,\net al, defendants, the undersigned,\nas Commissioner of said Court, will\noffer for sale at public vendue to the\nhighest bidder, at the West door or\nentrance of the County Courthouse,\nin which said Court is held, in the\nCounty of St. Frsincis within the\nhours prescribed by law for judicial\nsales, on\nTHURSDAY. THE 31ST DAY OF\nMARCH. A. D\u201e 15*7,\nfl* following described real estate,\nto-wit:\nThe Blast Half of the Southwest\nQuarter, (E)i_SWt4) of Section 21,\nand the North\" Half of the Northeast\nQuarter (Nh NE14) of Section 28,\nall in Township Six North, Range 2\nEast, and containing 164 acres, more\nor less, in St. Francis County, Ar\nkansas.\nTERMS OF SALE: On a credit\nof three months, the purchaser being\nrequired to execute a bond as re\nquired by law and the order and de\ncree of said Court in said cause, with\napproved security, bearing interest\nat the rate of 8 per cent per annum\nfrom date of sale until paid, and a\nlien being retained on the premises\nsold to secure the payment (of the\npurchase money.\nGiven under my hand this 9th\nday of March, AH)., 1927.\nt. r. MeDOUGAL,\n3-19-81. Commissioner in Chancery.\nMOTOR INDUSTRY\nEXPECTS A BIG,\nPROSPEROUS YEAR\nAn optimistic note on the spring:\nbusiness outlook in the automobile\nindustry, discounting: the \u2018saturation\npoint\u2019 bugaboo and pointing out\nfavorable conditions throughout the\ncountry, is sounded in a statement\njust issued by William S. Knudsen,\nPresident and General Manager of\nthe Chevrolet Motor Company.\n\u201cIn forecasting a continuance of\ngood business prospects for the\nSpring months, I am perhaps influ\nenced by the aspect of our own sales\nwhich have never been better in the\nhistory of the company,\u201d said Mr.\nKnudsen.\n\u201cAs evidencing steady growth in\nautomobile production during this\nperiod, statistics issued by the United\nStates Department of Commerce for I\nthe last three years covering the six\nmonths form January 1 to June 30\nare interesting. The figures for j\nthese years follow:\n1924 __ 2,054,561\n1925 .2,173,525\n1926 ..2,450,780\n\u201cWith these figures showing busi\nness on the upgrade generally, there\nare only two reasons which could\nbe advanced for a possible decrease\nin sales\u2014first, reaching the so-call\ned \u2018saturation point\u2019\u2014and second, a\ngeneral decline in business produc\ning a reactive tendency in buying.\n\u201cNo one has ever been able to ad\nvance any reasonable formula for\nfiguring the \u2018saturation point.\u2019 The\n\u2018two or more\u2019 ear trend is so pro\nnounced that former theories are be\ning constantly upset. If we knew\nthe total area which would be oc\ncupied if all cars produced were run\nwithin that area, making it impos\nsible for this space to accommodate\nany more cars, some basis would be\navailable for figuring \u2018saturation.\u2019\nj But such a situation is impossible\u2014\nand we may leave the \u2018saturation\n(point\u2019 for the future to determine,\nj inasmuch as the human mind will\nfind it possible to open up any bot\ntle-neck of traffic congestion which\nmight develop.\n\u201cAs for the general trend in busi\nness, country-wide reports show the\nusual spring activity is opening-up\ntwenty days ahead of schedule. With\nthe winter fairly mild, marked only\nby severity in spots, rapid accelera\ntion of municipal and private con\nstruction operations is indicated.\nFarming should start early due to the\ngood weather and manufacturing\noperations genex*ally are in excellent\ncondition.\n\u201cRapid turnover at smaller profits\nis the keynote throughout industry\nas reflected by our country\u2019s busi\nness. With this policy can only come\na demand for more transportation.\n\u201cThe shippers are demanding bet\nter freight service; the business\ntraveller is demanding better train\nservice and the automobile user is\ndemanding better service of his car,\nand the firm that is in a position to\nassure the buyer this better service\ncan have nothing but bright pros\npects for the spring of 1927.\u201d\nThere are 16,000 diamond mills\nin Belgium and 700 or more work\nshops for cutting the stones.\nCOMMISSIONER'S SALE\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN,\nThat in pursuance of the authority\nand directions contained in the de\ncretal order of the Chancery Court\nof St. Francis County, made and en\ntered on the 28th day of February,\nA. D.. 1927, in a certain cause (No.\n4837) then pending therein between\nFussell-Graham-Alderson Co., et al,\ncomplainants, and T. B. Sellers, et\nal, defendants, the undersigned, as\nCommissioner of said Court, will of\nfer for sale at public vendue to the\nhighest bidder, at the West door or\nentrance of the County Courthouse,\nin which said Court is held in the\nCounty of St. Francis, within the\nhours prescribed by law for judicial\nsales, on\nTHURSDAY. THE 3IST DAY OF\nMARCH. A. D\u201e 1927,\nthe following described real estate,\nto-wit:\nLots numbered Two (2), Nine (9),\nTen (10), Eleven (11). Twelve (12),\nThirteen (13), Fourteen (14), Sev\nenteen (17), Eighteen (18), Nine\nteen (19) and Twenty (20), also\none-hundred ten feet (110 ft)) off\nof the South end of Lot No. Three\n(3); all of said lots being in Block\nNo. Seven (7) of J. W. and Mrs. F.\nL. Moore\u2019s Sub-division of Blocks 5,\nj 7. 8. 9, and 17 of Graham A Howes'\nAddition to the town of Forrest City,\nArkansas.\nAlso a lot described as follows, to\nwit: Beginning at the Northeast\ncorner of Lot One (1) in Block Sev\nen (7) of J. W. and Mrs. F. L.\nMoore's Sub-division of Blocks 5, 7,\n8, 9 and 17 of Graham A Howes\u2019 Ad\ndition to the town of Forrest City:\nthence North Ninety-one (91) feet;\nthence West one-hundred eighty-nine\nfeet (189); thence South ninety-one\n(91) feet to the Northwest corner\nof said Lot One in said Block Seven\n(7); thence Fast one-hundred eighty\nnine (189) feet to the place of be\ngining. provided; the said sale shall\nhe subject to the unpaid balance of\npurchase money secured by vendor\u2019s\nlien in deed recorded at page 153\nof Deed Record 77 in St Francis\nCounty.\nTERMS OF SALE: On a credit\nof three months, the purchaser being\nrequired to execute a bond as re\nquired by law and the order and de\ncree of said Court in said cause, with\napproved security, bearing interest\nat the rate of 8 per cent per annum\nfrom date of sale until paid, and a\nlien being retained on the premises\nsold to secure the payment of the\npurchase money.\nGiven under my hand this 9th\nday of March, A. D., 1987.\nJ. F. McDOUGAL. j\n8-19-31. Commissioner in Chancery.\nFloor Varnish\nthat wears\nTHERE are only two reasons for varnish'\ning a floor\u2014to protect the surface of the\nwood\u2014to add beauty to the floor.\nTherefore a floor varnish must have\nqualities which will withstand the most severe\nabuse without marring and still retain its elav 1\nticity and toughness to act as a protector.\nPee Gee Floor Varnish has proved its worth\nin thousands of homes\u2014there is no better\nvarnish made.\nVACCARO-GROBMYER C0\u2018\nLUMBER\u2014FEED\u2014HARDWARE v\nFORREST CITY, ARKANSAS\nMATCH BLOWS UP AUTO\nilmette. 111.\u2014Georjre M. Ma\nson's car was blown up when a care\nless smoker threw a lighted match\nunder the machine, from which gaso-1\nline was leaking.\nI\nMoscow.\u2014Nine earthquake\nhave been felt along the Ural\ntains during the past month.\nshock*\nM*n>.\nEntertainment by the World\u2019s Best Artists\nover the\nRadio or by the Victrola\nCome and let us show you the new Atwater-Kents and the new Victrolas.\nthis evening\nLOOK at an Atwater Kent\nReceiving Set\u2014inside and\noat. Notice the workman\nship, the neatness, the\nbeautiful finish.\nTorn the dials yourselfand\nlisten to real all-round pa(^\nformance\u2014the tone and\nvolume, distance and so*\nIsctivity. We know that, if\nyou do thoee things jroo\u2019l\nnever be conten